Project Requirements for SafeHaven
To develop SafeHaven as a functional and user-friendly platform, the following requirements
need to be considered:
1. Functional Requirements
a. Location Safety Analysis
• Fetch crime data for a location (real-time API or database).
• Show safety ratings based on crime rates and user reports.
• Provide nighttime safety insights.
c. User Reviews & Community Insights
• Allow users to submit safety reviews & ratings for locations.
• Implement moderation to prevent spam or fake reviews.
d. Safe Zones & Business Listings
• Highlight women-friendly locations (cafés, hostels, police stations, etc.).
• Enable businesses to register & verify their listings.
e. Search & Filters
• Search locations by name, category, or safety score.
• Filter by crime type, time of day, or user ratings.
g. User Authentication & Profiles
• Secure sign-up/login (email, Google, social login).
• Allow users to save favorite locations and past searches.
2. Non-Functional Requirements
a. Performance & Scalability
• Handle large datasets efficiently (crime reports, user reviews).
• Ensure fast response times for search and safety analysis.
b. Security & Privacy
• Encrypt user data and location history.
• Implement secure API authentication.
c. Cross-Platform Compatibility
• Responsive design for web and mobile.
• Consider a mobile app for real-time safety updates.
d User-Friendly UI/UX
• Clean, intuitive interface for easy navigation.
• Dark mode for nighttime usage.
Stakeholders of SafeHaven
SafeHaven involves multiple stakeholders who contribute to and benefit from the platform.
These include:
1. Primary Stakeholders (Directly Impacted)
a. Women & General Users – The main users who rely on SafeHaven for location safety
insights, reviews, and alerts.
b. Business Owners – Cafés, hostels, and other women-friendly establishments listed on the
platform to attract customers.
c. Law Enforcement Agencies – Police and security officials who can use the data for safety
monitoring and crime prevention.
2. Secondary Stakeholders (Indirectly Impacted)
1. Government & NGOs – Organizations working on women's safety can use SafeHaven’s
insights for policy-making and intervention.
2. Data Providers & Researchers – Institutions using crime data and user reports for safety
analytics and studies.
Tech Stack
1. Frontend: React.js (for a dynamic and interactive UI)
2. Backend: Node.js with Express.js (for API handling and server-side logic)
3. Database: SQL (PostgreSQL/MySQL) for structured data storage
SafeHaven: Empowering Women with Safer Choices
What is SafeHaven?
SafeHaven is a community-driven platform designed to help women assess the safety of
locations based on crime rates, user reviews, and nighttime safety insights. It highlights safe
zones such as women-friendly cafés, hostels, and police stations to support informed and
confident decision-making.
Why is SafeHaven Useful?
• Informed Decision-Making – Helps users choose safer routes and locations by
providing safety ratings based on verified crime data and community input.
• Community-Powered Safety – User-generated reviews and insights foster a trusted
network of real experiences and local knowledge.
• Location-Based Insights – Offers visibility into how safe a place is, especially during
nighttime hours.
Why is it a Great Idea for Women’s and Public Safety?
• Crime Prevention – Increases awareness of potentially unsafe areas through
transparent data sharing.
• Confidence & Independence – Enables women to move more freely by providing
access to safety-related information.
• Support Network – Encourages women to share safety tips and insights, helping
others avoid risky areas.
Why Should We Use SafeHaven?
• Trustworthy & Data-Driven – Combines official crime reports with user reviews to
ensure credibility and relevance.
• User-Friendly – Clean and intuitive interface for checking safety scores, reading
community reviews, and finding safe spaces.
• Community Impact – Promotes collective responsibility for public safety by
encouraging users to contribute and stay informed.
SafeHaven isn’t just an app—it’s a movement towards a safer, more informed world. 
